					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Everything is in the title. I have always implemented music engines where the note N째0 is C, etc up to note N째11 which is B. It would seem that C is the "first note".
<br />However, A is the only note which has a rational frequency (440Hz, other notes have irrational frequencies calculated from the mid-A pitch).
<br />And the lower available note the NES' APU channels can play is A (okay, PAL NESes can reach Ab, but why would you compose music that only works with PAL ?).
<br />Also, the fact that the first letter, A, is agigned to A and not C probably have historically something about A being the "first note" of the scale.
<br />
<br />For these reasons, I'm considering switching to a system where note N째0 would be A, and note N째11 would be Ab/G#.
<br />
<br />I'd just have to change octave shifts in my data, wich is quickly done.
<br />Any ideas?</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
